// FizzBuzz — the classic, the Sutra way. No `if`: the four cases are a
// softmax-weighted superposition (`select`), and the winning branch's
// String dominates the output.
// @embedding: none dim=64
//
// The scores lean on two 2026-07-08 semantics fixes:
//   - `(n % 3) == 0` uses the exact number-equality indicator
//     (+1 at equal, -1 at |diff| >= 1) — zero-testing reads true;
//   - the truth values cast to numbers via `(number)`, the one
//     axis-moving cast pair.
// The ×10 gain sharpens the softmax so the winner carries ~all the
// weight (same idiom as fuzzy_dispatch.su).

function string fizzbuzz(int n) {
    number s3 = (number) ((n % 3) == 0);
    number s5 = (number) ((n % 5) == 0);
    return select(
        [10 * (s3 + s5),
         10 * (s3 - s5),
         10 * (s5 - s3),
         10 * (0 - s3 - s5)],
        [make_string("fizzbuzz"), make_string("fizz"),
         make_string("buzz"), int_to_string(n)]);
}

// The REAL FizzBuzz: loop 1..15, accumulating one String. This is the
// workload that motivated loop-calls-as-expressions (round-26: it was a
// parse error) and vector-valued loop state (finding 2026-07-08: a String
// accumulator was crushed to a scalar) — both shipped 2026-07-12, so the
// classic now writes the classic way: an iterative_loop threads the
// String accumulator, and the expression form returns its final state.
iterative_loop build(15, String acc) {
    pass string_concat(string_concat(acc, fizzbuzz(iterator)), make_string(" "));
}

function string main() {
    return loop build(15, make_string(""));
}
